<div id="banner">
	<h1>Where&#8217;s Shakespeare?</h1>
</div>

<div class="content">
<p>&#8220;What is <a href="http://www.bookcrossing.com/">BookCrossing</a>, you ask? [&#8230;] the books our members leave in the wild <i>are free</i>&#8230; but it&#8217;s the act of <i>freeing</i> books that points to the heart of BookCrossing. Book trading has never been more exciting, more serendipitous, than with BookCrossing. Our goal, simply, is to <i>make the whole world a library</i>. BookCrossing is a <i>book exchange</i> of infinite proportion, the first and only of its kind. [&#8230;] It&#8217;s also a <i>fascinating exercise</i> in fate, karma, or whatever you want to call the chain of events that can occur between two or more lives and one piece of literature.&#8221;</p>

<p>It&#8217;s like <a href="http://www.wheresgeorge.com/">Where&#8217;s George?</a> except with books&#8230; and you give them away.</p>

<p class="posted">posted August 05, 2002 11:17 PM (<a class="category" href="http://www.aaronsw.com/weblog/cat_web_memes">Web Memes</a>)  <a href="000475" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
</div>

